Talking Points

J.D. Oder

1. Thank you for taking the time to meet us today. We are always available, 24/7, to discuss any
   issues that CardConnect has with its relationship with Shift4.

2.  Frankly, that is one of the many problems here. CardConnect rarely speaks with, or meets with,
    Shift4 about issues that CardConnect has with Shift4, and instead prefers to communicate through
    its lawyers, which does not create a good relationship.

3.  Like most vendors that provide services to merchants, Shift4 desires to have good relationships
    with all ISO's and payment facilitators that use Shift4 as the gateway to provide tokenization
    and gateway services.

4.  Shift4 is very proud of its technology, which is significantly better than the technology relied
    upon by CardConnect and its parent, First Data.

5.  That is one of the sources of friction in the relationship, as Shift4 would prefer that CardConnect
    rely entirely on Shift4's technology and abandon the legacy technology.

6.  Everyone in the payments industry knows that Shift4's technology is the best: fastest, most
    secure and feature rich. By way of example, no company in the world comes close to providing
    the same level of security for their merchants as Shift4, as it is the only entity that provides the
    only solution, that is certified by a third party lab, to provide both P2PE and tokenization. That is
    years ahead of anyone else.

7.  Likewise, Shift4 has numerous unique services not offered by any other processor - all of which
    are designed to enhance CardConnect's own product offering.

8.  Despite Shift4 offering all of these superior offerings, it appears that CardConnect, for some
    reason, prefers to do business with those that do not have a similar offering, like FreedomPay
    (competitor of Shift4).

9.  I would like to better understand why that is.

10. 1also would like to better understand why CardConnect continually files disputes with
    Shift4 based upon false and fraudulent claims made by CardConnect's merchants,
    against Shift4.

11. No other ISO or payfac does that.

12. Can you help me to understand why CardConnect does that?

13. Another sensitive topic is the topic of "Saab 35."

14. As you know, Shift4 has always believed that its technology is unique and adds significant value
    to any reseller of its technology.

15. We would like to talk to you about that, as we want to explore creative solutions to that issue, so
    that CardConnect can remain a reseller while at the same time providing fair value to Shift4
    with respect to its technology.

16. To do this effectively, however, we need to see the actual agreement between CardConnect and
    its customer, so that we can see how they are pricing the technology and services provided to
    the merchant.

17. Also, can we talk candidly about the future payments landscape, and determine if there is a
    way for Shift4 to compensate CardConnect for the payments it makes under Saab 35?

18. We are open to all ideas, as we are willing to take a calculated risk, in order to facilitate

Talking Points

J.D, Oder

    1. Thank you for taking the time to meet us today. We are always available, 24/7, to discuss any
       issues that CardConnect has with its relationship with Shift4.

    2. Frankly, that is one of the many problems here. CardConnect rarely speaks with, or meets with,
       Shift4 about issues that CardConnect has with Shift4, and instead prefers to communicate through
       its lawyers, which does not create a good relationship.

    3. Like most vendors that provide services to merchants, Shift4 desires to have good relationships
       with all ISO's and payment facilitators that use Shift4 as the gateway to provide tokenization
       and gateway services.

    4, Shift4 is very proud of its technology, which is significantly better than the technology relied
       upon by CardConnect and its parent, First Data.

    5. That is one of the sources of friction in the relationship, as Shift4 would prefer that CardConnect
       rely entirely on Shift4's technology and abandon the legacy technology.

Talking Points

J.D. Oder

1. Thank you for taking the time to meet us today. We are always available, 24/7, to discuss any
   issues that CardConnect has with its relationship with Shift4.

2.  Frankly, that is one of the many problems here. CardConnect rarely speaks with, or meets with,
    Shift4 about issues that CardConnect has with Shift4, and instead prefers to communicate through
    its lawyers, which does not create a good relationship.

3.  Like most vendors that provide services to merchants, Shift4 desires to have good relationships
    with all ISO's and payment facilitators that use Shift4 as the gateway to provide tokenization
    and gateway services.

4.  Shift4 is very proud of its technology, which is significantly better than the technology relied
    upon by CardConnect and its parent, First Data.

5.  That is one of the sources of friction in the relationship, as Shift4 would prefer that CardConnect
    rely entirely on Shift4's technology and abandon the legacy technology.

6.  Everyone in the payments industry knows that Shift4's technology is the best: fastest, most
    secure and feature rich. By way of example, no company in the world comes close to providing
    the same level of security for their merchants as Shift4, as it is the only entity that provides the
    only solution, that is certified by a third party lab, to provide both P2PE and tokenization. That is
    years ahead of anyone else.

7.  Likewise, Shift4 has numerous unique services not offered by any other processor - all of which
    are designed to enhance CardConnect's own product offering.

8.  Despite Shift4 offering all of these superior offerings, it appears that CardConnect, for some
    reason, prefers to do business with those that do not have a similar offering, like FreedomPay
    (competitor of Shift4).

9.  I would like to better understand why that is.

10. 1also would like to better understand why CardConnect continually files disputes with
    Shift4 based upon false and fraudulent claims made by CardConnect's merchants,
    against Shift4.

11. No other ISO or payfac does that.

12. Can you help me to understand why CardConnect does that?

13. Another sensitive topic is the topic of "Saab 35."

14. As you know, Shift4 has always believed that its technology is unique and adds significant value
    to any reseller of its technology.

15. We would like to talk to you about that, as we want to explore creative solutions to that issue, so
    that CardConnect can remain a reseller while at the same time providing fair value to Shift4
    with respect to its technology.

16. To do this effectively, however, we need to see the actual agreement between CardConnect and
    its customer, so that we can see how they are pricing the technology and services provided to
    the merchant.

17. Also, can we talk candidly about the future payments landscape, and determine if there is a
    way for Shift4 to compensate CardConnect for the payments it makes under Saab 35?

18. We are open to all ideas, as we are willing to take a calculated risk, in order to facilitate

    I, J.D. Oder, II, pursuant to 28 U.S.C. § 1746, declare under penalty of perjury that
    the following statements are true and correct:
        1. I am over the age of eighteen and am competent to testify as to the matters
    contained in this Declaration. The statements set forth below are based on my personal
    knowledge.
        2. Currently, I serve as the President and Chief Executive Officer of Shift4
    Payments, LLC and related entities (“Shift4”). I have held this full-time position since October of
    2014.
        3. Previously, I served in various leadership roles at, what is now, JP Morgan
    Chase (“Chase”).
        4. After leaving Chase, I joined a payments-related company, Merchant Link, as
    the company’s Chief Executive Officer (“CEO”). I was also a member of Merchant Link’s Board
    of Directors. I began my tenure as CEO of Merchant Link on or about July 12, 2012. I was
    recruited for that role by FTV Capital.
        5. I am a named inventor on U.S. Patent No. 10,600,068 (the “ ‘068 Patent”).
    The ‘068 patent covers technology generally related to systems for securing payment card data.
        6. I have served and continue to serve as an expert witness in a variety of
    intellectual property cases. In that time, I have seen first-hand the value of intellectual property
    rights.
        7. Defendant, Jared Isaacman, likes to portray himself as a “daredevil”
    entrepreneur. My experience has been that Mr. Isaacman routinely and frequently crosses the line
    in the name of self-promotion and personal gain. For example, in the past Mr. Isaacman purchased
    a military-grade F-16 fighter jet.
